CA9 Data Validation¶

  1. CA9 is expressed in >95% of RCCs, but not normal tissue
    1. Q: What percentage of tumor samples are over-expressed?
  2. Hypothesized to be on the surface of other tumor cells
    1. Q: What percentage of tumor samples in other tissues are over-expressed?
  3. HIF pathway
    1. Q: Will RCCs cluster with other tissues for this gene subset?
  4. VEGF pathway is the most popular targeted pathway in RCCs.
    1. Q: Will RCCs cluster with other tissues for this gene subset?

from __future__ import division

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import holoviews as hv
hv.extension('bokeh')

I. What percentage of RCC samples are over-expressed?¶

Two approaches:

  • Differential expression
  • Outlier analysis (upper / lower quartile)
    • Use all of GTEx to get a baseline distribution
    • Use kidney normal samples for baseline distribution

Read in metadata and expression dataframe

A L2FC of 2 or more is typically considered significant, and >95% of tumor samples have a larger L2FC.

                kdims=[hv.Dimension('Expression', unit='log2(x+1)')], label='KDE of CA9 in Normal Tissues')
Out[108]:

Not exactly a normal distribution, but we can stil compute upper and lower bounds

In [123]:
upper, lower = h.iqr_bounds(df[df.tumor == 'no']['CA9'].apply(lambda x: np.log2(x+1)))
print 'Upper Bound for Kidney CA9: {}'.format(round(upper, 2))

Upper Bound for Kidney CA9: 10.8

tumor_ca9 = df[(df.tissue == 'Kidney') & (df.tumor == 'yes')]['CA9'].apply(h.l2norm)
perc = len([x for x in tumor_ca9 if x > upper]) / len(tumor_ca9)
print 'Number of tumor samples greater than upper bound: {}'.format(round(perc, 2))

Number of tumor samples greater than upper bound: 0.93
